2026-07-16 SCOPE DECISION + RENDERER: this map now RENDERS (artifact/critical-minerals-map.html), the first map other than 01 that can.
  SCOPE, decided on the repo's own precedent rather than taste: a Keystone map DOES admit its downstream buyers as nodes. 01-semiconductor already carries GM, BMW, Lenovo and HP as `oem`, and 11 of its 48 edges touch a system firm. GM and BMW in a chip map are exactly analogous to Tesla and Ford here. So Syrah's offtakes were never out of scope, my company list was just too short. Added 6 downstream nodes (Tesla Inc, Ford Motor Company, Lucid Group, LG Energy Solution, Samsung SDI, POSCO Future M) with blank financials, which the gate's incomplete-does-not-fail rule accepts as honest.
  MEASURED FIRST, then built (the spike was worth ~3 minutes): running 01's builder against 02's data succeeded with EXIT 0 and rendered a map where 30 of 33 companies landed in NO layer, because 01's LAYERS are hardcoded to semiconductor roles (ip-eda, foundry, osat) and this map's roles are miner/refiner/separator. It did not crash. A map-specific renderer fails SILENTLY on another map's data, same shape as the chokepoint bug. That measurement is now a permanent selftest fixture in shared/build_map.py.
  02's map.json declares an 11-layer minerals taxonomy (miner -> trader -> refiner -> separator -> chemicals -> anode/cathode -> magnets -> cells -> recyclers -> oem). Zero orphans. Verified in a real browser: 33 companies, 14 relationships, 5 chokepoints, value chain populated (Miners 21, Traders 2, Refiners 19, Separators 4), all 8 tabs, no JS errors, and storage key `critical-minerals-map:v1` is DISTINCT from `semiconductor-map:v1` so the two maps cannot clobber each other's watchlist. It also inherited durable-state v2.0.0 for free.
  NEXT: financials for the 5 chokepoints (Chinese A-share filers, expect tier 2/3 and label them so), refresh the stale 2019 Glencore edge, and publish this map as its own artifact.
2026-07-16 SYRAH EDGES (+3, now 17): resumed the ORIGINAL Lynas/Syrah worker rather than respawning, so it still had the annual reports loaded. 3 offtake edges: Syrah -> Tesla Inc (t1), Syrah -> Lucid Group (t1), Syrah -> POSCO Future M (t1, medium). Dependency mix improved to 9/17 (was 6/14).
  🔴 THE WORKER CAUGHT A REAL ERROR IN ITS OWN EARLIER REPORT, AND ONLY BECAUSE THE PROMPT SAID "RE-OPEN THE SOURCE, DO NOT AUTHOR FROM YOUR SUMMARY". Its first pass had listed Ford, LG Energy Solution, Samsung SDI and POSCO as counterparties "in Syrah's FY2025 Annual Report". Re-reading the actual PDF: that report contains ZERO occurrences of any of those four. It had silently blended web-search chatter into what it attributed to the document. ITS ONE "FORD" HIT WAS A CASE-INSENSITIVE MATCH ON "ABBOTSFORD", THE SUBURB IN THE SHARE REGISTRY'S POSTAL ADDRESS. It then ran a control (Tesla/Lucid/Balama return hits) and a NEGATIVE control (Volkswagen returns 0) to prove the null was real and not a broken search. That is the sentinel discipline, executed by a Sonnet worker, unprompted.
  🔴 AND IT INDICTED MY OWN CHECKER. tools/verify_edges.py used a bare substring match, so it had the identical bug: named("Vale S.A.", "cobalt is prevalent") returned TRUE, because "prevalent" contains "vale". I had already reported "14/14 verified" using that matcher. Fixed to word-bounded matching (\b kills both Abbotsford and prevalent), added the 6 downstream nodes to the KEY map, and kept BOTH real cases as permanent selftest fixtures. RE-VERIFIED all 14 previously merged edges under the stricter matcher: 14/14 still pass. So the green was CORRECT but UNEARNED; the conclusion held and the method did not. Reporting that distinction is the point.
  HONEST OMISSIONS the worker made and I am keeping: Ford/LG/Samsung SDI have only NON-BINDING MoUs "to evaluate AAM supply ... and progress towards binding offtake agreements" in FY2023/FY2024, and vanish entirely from FY2025, suggesting they never converted. No vocabulary term fits "agreement to evaluate", and writing offtake-with would have been an overclaim.
  ⚠ TWO FRAGILITIES A READER MUST NOT MISS: (1) the POSCO row is tier 1 but confidence=medium and sourced to FY2024, because FY2025 does not mention POSCO at all and FY2023 said the offtake required POSCO's notification by 31 Dec 2025 to commence. It may have lapsed. The worker refused to date the row to a document that does not support it. (2) The Tesla offtake is UNDER AN ACTIVE DEFAULT NOTICE: FY2025 discloses Tesla alleged Syrah defaulted on conforming AAM samples, cure deadline 1 June 2026, after which Tesla may terminate. The edge stands but is more fragile than a plain offtake row conveys.

