TICKER COLLISION, CAUGHT BEFORE IT LANDED. The candidate list came from matching 02's ticker column against
SEC company_tickers.json. "NEO" matched CIK 1077183 = NEOGENOMICS INC, a cancer diagnostics company. 02's NEO
is Neo Performance Materials, a rare-earth magnet maker listed in Toronto that does not file with the SEC.
Ticker-only matching would have written an oncology lab's revenue into a rare-earth row, and NOTHING here
would have caught it: the row would have been complete, sourced, tier 1 and wrong. The gate checks that a
costed row HAS a source, never that the source is about the same company. Fix applied: verify the SEC
REGISTRANT NAME against the company name before fetching. Neo Performance Materials stays uncosted.

Concept forks, adjudicated by printing every candidate at the reporting year before writing:
- BHP: profit attributable to owners 9.019 vs consolidated ProfitLoss 11.143 -> used attributable. The
  consolidated line would have overstated BHP's bottom line by 24%.
- BHP's fiscal year ends 30 JUNE; the period taken is FY2025 ending 2025-06-30, not a December year.
- Rio Tinto: attributable 9.966 vs consolidated 10.249; no cash-flow capex tag, so capex is IFRS PP&E
  additions 12.924 (noted in the row), the same fallback used for Vale.
- Ford: us-gaap NetIncomeLoss is NOT tagged for FY2025, only ProfitLoss (-8.162). Used it and said so in the
  row rather than pass a consolidated figure off as attributable.
- USA Rare Earth and Ford tag capex as PaymentsToAcquireProductiveAssets, not ...PropertyPlantAndEquipment.

LEFT EMPTY ON PURPOSE:
- Lithium Americas REVENUE: pre-revenue (Thacker Pass under construction); the filing carries no revenue tag
